      "message": "\u003e I agree, this patchset itself is unlikely to directly break anything.  \nI\u0027m worried about future regressions where object_path is now default \nconstructable with a path that isn\u0027t obviously incorrect as Alexander \ngives in his example.  That example would compile and run, but is now \nsilently incorrect because there\u0027s no correct daemon that directly adds \nobjects at the root anymore.\n\nSo the application may have crashed, and with this patch it (or its clients) does not crash anymore. Is that a regression to you?\n\nNote that a single application may expose various object paths under various namespaces. IMO a failure to initialize an object path properly should not have a blast radius larger than necessary.\n\n\u003e  but is now silently incorrect\n\nHow did you come to this conclusion? Usually applications provide a highly visible `lg2::error` message if they encounter unexpected / missing values / object paths on D-Bus and still continue with other tasks instead of crashing.\n\n\u003e \u003e We can alternatively fix the generated code to ensure it never sends out a bogus object_path, right?\n\n\u003e This would be my mid-strong preference to avoid footguns in default constructing an objects and forgetting to declare a path.\n\nThat\u0027s just a partial fix and on top of that it\u0027s conceptually inconsistent. Why should an object path as part of a generated server produce a different default value than when it\u0027s constructed independently?\n\nThe default constructor is wrong so it should be fixed or go away. The problem is not just in the generated code.\nIf we accept this `\"\"` as our internal state then technically every function receiving an object path would need do object path validation. It\u0027s like needing to check `int*` for `nullptr`.\n\n\u003e @alexander, was there a real piece of code that had a default \ninitialized bug that drove this, or was this just wanting to use \nobject_path in more places?\n\nI hit this bug sometimes but i do not remember the specific patch. Since i tested my code i changed over to pass the properties to initialize the interface.\n\nSo yes, it\u0027s a real bug that people can hit and unnecessarily error prone API in combination with the generated server.",
