      "writtenOn": "2026-03-19T15:04:19Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e Wait..... how does that happen?  The broker should be rejecting any path\n that\u0027s invalid.  Do you have an example of how this could occur?  If \nit\u0027s possible, that changes some of my feelings on this.  I would expect\n the current behavior to be some kind of client crash (either a bus \ndisconnect, or thrown exception on initialize())\n\nIf you use the generated server and client, both of them will get an exception.\nHere is the diff on top of PS2:\n\n```\nindex b9eceb1..a1d57e9 100644\n--- a/test/gen/test_aserver_construct_with_object_path.cpp\n+++ b/test/gen/test_aserver_construct_with_object_path.cpp\n@@ -1,23 +1,51 @@\n+#include \"client.hpp\"\n #include \"sdbusplus/async.hpp\"\n #include \"server/Test/aserver.hpp\"\n \n #include \u003csdbusplus/async/context.hpp\u003e\n \n #include \u003cgtest/gtest.h\u003e\n+#include \u003ciostream\u003e\n \n class A : public sdbusplus::aserver::server::Test\u003cA\u003e\n {};\n \n+\n+\n+sdbusplus::async::task\u003c\u003e mytask(sdbusplus::async::context\u0026 ctx, const sdbusplus::message::object_path\u0026 path){\n+\n+    auto client \u003d sdbusplus::client::server::Test(ctx)\n+    .path(path.str).service(\"xyz.openbmc_project.Test\");\n+\n+    auto p \u003d co_await client.object_path();\n+    std::cout \u003c\u003c p.str \u003c\u003c std::endl;\n+    ctx.request_stop();\n+    co_return;\n+}\n+\n // Test that we can construct with an object path\n TEST(AServerConstructWithObjectPath, NoProps)\n {\n     sdbusplus::async::context ctx;\n \n-    sdbusplus::message::object_path path(\"/\");\n+    char* rolePtr \u003d std::getenv(\"ROLE\");\n+    if (rolePtr \u003d\u003d nullptr){\n+        return;\n+    }\n+    const std::string role(rolePtr);\n+\n+    sdbusplus::message::object_path path(\"/xyz/openbmc_project/my_buggy_server\");\n \n-    sdbusplus::aserver::server::Test\u003cA\u003e t2(ctx, path);\n+    if (role \u003d\u003d \"client\"){\n+        ctx.spawn(mytask(ctx, path));\n+        ctx.run();\n+    }\n \n-    EXPECT_EQ(t2.object_path(), \"/\");\n+    if (role \u003d\u003d \"server\"){\n+        sdbusplus::aserver::server::Test\u003cA\u003e t2(ctx, path);\n+        ctx.request_name(\"xyz.openbmc_project.Test\");\n+        ctx.run();\n+    }\n }\n \n // Test that we can construct with an object path (the overload with properties\n```\n\nHow to use it?\n```\nROLE\u003dserver ./build/test/test_aserver_construct_with_object_path\n...\nterminate called after throwing an instance of \u0027sdbusplus::exception::SdBusError\u0027\n  what():  sd_bus_process discard: org.freedesktop.DBus.Error.InvalidArgs: Invalid argument\nAborted                    (core dumped) ROLE\u003dserver ./build/test/test_aserver_construct_with_object_path\n```\nand client\n```\nROLE\u003dclient ./build/test/test_aserver_construct_with_object_path\n...\nterminate called after throwing an instance of \u0027sdbusplus::exception::SdBusError\u0027\n  what():  method: org.freedesktop.DBus.Error.NoReply: Remote peer disconnected\nAborted                    (core dumped) ROLE\u003dclient ./build/test/test_aserver_construct_with_object_path\n```\n\nThe server default initializes the object path property to \"\" (current buggy behavior) and then 2 days later when the client actually tries to read the property, both of them get an exception.\n\nNow exceptions can be caught and signals can be handled, but we can prevent this class of bug entirely by\n\n- default construction to a valid object path (focus of this patch). This would already prevent the bug.\n\n- perhaps implementing some checks into `object_path` constructor to throw an exception when an invalid path is passed (this would also make similar bugs show up as soon as the server starts, but requires extra cycles)\n\n\n\u003e Please point to code where that happens.\n\nYou can construct such a bug with any aserver that has object path properties.\nSimply use the first constructor without passing properties and you will achieve the bug.\n\nRepeating myself here, but i can\u0027t point to any merged example where the bug happens. People test their code and are aware of these problems.\n\nAgain, working and bug-free code does not imply the underlying APIs or libraries are good design or bug free.\n\nPeople have built linux on top of raw pointers and C code and yet it still works super reliable.\n\n\u003e Would\u0027ve also preferred some more characters in there to make clear that\n the code is broken if you ever see this, but what\u0027s there is enough.\n\nSince you did not provide any preferred value, i am keeping it as `/invalid` for now. As long as it\u0027s a single path segment we can always adjust the value at a later point since it\u0027s not meant for code to rely on it.",
